Savory Croissant Strata Recipe - Prep ahead Christmas Eve and bake Christmas morning so you can enjoy the time with family:)

Ingredients:
7-8 croissants (Let sit out for a day or two in container.)
5 eggs 
1 c. Cream
1 c. Milk 
A couple dashes of salt and pinch of pepper
1/2 tsp. garlic powder
1/4 tsp. Cayenne pepper
2 tbls. Dijon mustard
1/3 c. chopped green onions
2 c. thin sliced ham chopped into pieces (can substitute with bacon or sausage!)
1 c. Shredded cheddar or gouda
1 1/2 c. shredded cheddar or gouda for topping

Instructions:
-Tear apart croissants into chunks and align in buttered 9x13 in pyrex dish.
-Toast in the oven for 3 min. on 400 ° 
-In a mixing bowl, beat eggs. Mix in cream, milk, salt, pepper, garlic powder, cayenne pepper, dijon mustard, green onions, ham, and cheese.
-Pour mixture over toasted croissant pieces, and use a fork to spread out evenly. 
-Sprinkle shredded gruyere, Swiss, or whatever cheese you have on hand on top! 
-Cover with greased foil and refrigerate for an hour (but best overnight!).
-Bake on convection setting at 350° for 45 min. You can remove foil for last ten minutes if you want it a little toasty on top!
-Serve warm with a side of fresh fruit! ✨
Makes 12 servings.

Recipe is also on our blog if you’d like to print! (inhonorofdesign.com)

✨Nutella Starbread Recipe to save for Christmas Eve or NYE! ✨ A favorite holiday dessert around here! *You can use pillsbury dough sheets as a shortcut.*

Dough ingredients:
* 1 cup warm milk
* 1 tablespoon instant dry yeast
* 2 tablespoons white granulated sugar
* 1 teaspoon salt
* 3 tablespoons salted butter softened
* 1 large egg
* 3 cups all-purpose flour (add more if needed until dough forms)

Other ingredients needed:
- 1 jar nutella
- About 1 stick butter
- Powdered sugar to sprinkle on top

INSTRUCTIONS
For dough: 
In a mixer, combine warm milk, yeast, sugar, salt, butter, and eggs. Add in flour. Use a dough hook and turn on to a low to medium speed until dough is formed. Place a lightly greased mixing bowl. Cover with a towel and let rise until double in size, about 1 hour.

 For star bread:
1.  Divide dough into 4 even pieces, and let sit for another 15 min. 
2. Roll first dough piece into a 10”-11″ circle onto parchment paper.
3. Place a bowl on top to trim edges.
4. Spread a layer of softened butter followed by a layer of Nutella leaving a little space around the edges.
5. Repeat with two more layers.
6. Lay the 4th layer of dough on top, and lay a 3”-4” circular object at the center. (I used a mug top.)
7. Use a knife or scissors to make 12 evenly cut sections of dough.
8. Take two side by side sections, and twist them away from each other two and half times.
9. Pinch the ends together well. 
10. Repeat with the remaining dough until you have a *6* point star.
11. Brush with melted butter.
12. Let the star bread sit for 30 min. 
Bake at 350° for about 20 min. or until slightly golden.
Remove from oven and sprinkle with powdered sugar. 

Best served warm with family, friends, or the neighbor who needs company this holiday season. 😉

#starbread #holidayrecipe #nutellastarbread #holidaydessert

Family recipe: Brioche French Toast Casserole Gotta make those eggs 

1 loaf of brioche bread (a little stale is even better)
5-6 eggs
2 c. milk
3/4 c. Heavy cream
1 tbls. Vanilla extract
2 tbls. Pure maple syrup
1 tsp. cinnamon
1/2 tsp. Nutmeg
1/2 tsp. salt
Fresh fruit

- Butter a 9x13 in. Pyrex
- Slice brioche bread in half diagonally and layer into the Pyrex 
- Mix milk, cream, vanilla, cinnamon, nutmeg, salt, and pure maple together in a bowl.
- Refrigerate for 30 min. to an hour (or overnight!)
- Bake on 350° covered in foil for 40 min. Remove foil and bake an additional 10 min. or until golden.
- Top with blueberries or strawberries, powdered sugar,  and maple syrup to preference. 
*Makes about 9-10 servings

My greatest influences. 🤍 Using #internationalwomensday as an excuse to honor my grandmothers, mother, and sisters:)

My grandma Lucia only knew Spanish when she and my grandpa chose to move their family from San Antonio to Lexington, KY. Her small and mighty kitchen was always open to whomever needed a warm cooked meal. She was fiery and funny. Rumor has it, once killed a snake with her bare hands to protect her children. She had a hat collection that she would rotate to wear to church on Sundays. She loved her family fiercely.

My grandma Margaret was an oil painter for my grandpa who was a photographer. She raised 10 children out of the same home in a small german town in OH, across the street from the church where she would sing in the choir. She still lives there today where a steady stream of children, grandchildren, and great grandchildren love to visit. She has always been both graceful and witty, creative, bright, and personal….wanting to know the details of everyone’s lives, and somehow remembering them. 

My own mother has always been my example of perseverance, faith through hardship, creativity in motherhood and family traditions, and the ability to love and listen to anyone she meets. She is my personal hero.

My sisters - the friendships that have been the best companions in my life. Pillars of strength and love.

When women live out their own unique purpose and love with their own unique heartbeat - the impact knows no bounds to the world around them! Never underestimate your worth! 🤍

I need super easy and minimal ingredients these days! Filmed this in a rush, but wanted to share my go-to quiche recipe that you can adapt with whatever ingredients you have on hand! Quick to prep and hearty and delish to eat!
_________

Savory Quiche Recipe

Ham and Cheese:
* 1 deep dish refrigerated pie crust (I use pillsbury)
* 4 large eggs
* 1/2 c. heavy cream
* 1/2 c. Milk
* 1/2 tsp dried mustard powder
* 1/2 tsp salt
* 1/4 tsp pepper
* 1 c. chopped thin sliced ham
* 1 c. shredded cheese (Swiss, pepper jack, or sharp cheddar)
* Optional: top with chopped chives

Bacon and Feta:
Same recipe as above except substitute bacon for ham, feta or goat cheese for cheddar, and add in 1 c. Chopped fresh spinach.

Blend eggs, milk, cream, salt, pepper, and any veggies. Sprinkle meat and cheese on the bottom of the pie crust and pour egg mixture on top.

Cover edges in foil and Bake on 350° for 45-55 min. or until middle is solid. (I overcooked mine here but can be slightly golden.) Remove and let sit for 10 min. Serve warm with fresh fruit and cinnamon rolls and you have Easter brunch! 

#brunchforacrowd 
#easterbrunch

Our new old home:) Built in 1860 in the heart of the small town my mom was raised in. My neighbors are my sister, aunts and uncles, and cousins. My grandma is one street over, and the school is down the street. I grew up in OH, and visited here just about every summer and holiday. It feels quite surreal to be here for the long haul! We can honestly say this is the first house and town that immediately has felt like HOME. 

I’ll share a tour on stories today!

🥹 A moment we will never forget. 
We were in the middle of hauling in moving boxes when we heard voices and music outside. This is what we walked out to. Our lawn was filled with familiar faces- Aunts and uncles, cousins, and even a few of my sisters. 

We have felt like nomads in a way…always seeking a place to plant roots. This felt like a big welcome home at the end of a long journey which is why I couldn’t stop the tears. 

We have felt so deeply that just as Harry Bailey reminds George at the end of It’s A Wonderful Life…it really is a true wealth to be surrounded by loved ones. We’re home!

Blessingway ceremonies have been around a while! Originally started from Native American tradition, and now being adapted into different variations/cultures.  I hosted one for my sister Angela a few weeks ago, to surround her in prayer and loving support as she prepared for the birth of her baby!

A few things we did:

✨1. Each person takes a votive candle and lights it before beginning. An opening prayer is read followed by 10 empowering scriptures. A rose is given to the mother to be for each scripture.

✨ 2. The votive candle is taken home by each person who attends the Blessingway. When the mother goes into labor, a notification is sent out and everyone lights their candle in prayer and unity for her and her baby.

✨3. Each person writes a personal note during the Blessingway on a notecard for the mother to take home and read. You can have each person add a bead to a chain as they give her the note for the mother to have a visual of all of her friends and family who are supporting her in birth.

✨ 4. A Blessingway is not a baby shower, but you can have the option of gifts. Everyone brought essentials she needed re-stocking on since this was baby #4.

Drinks and appetizers were served and time spent together was life giving for all. I’m so grateful to have this time in the same town as my sister, and this home to gather loved ones.

✨ I shared the scriptures, candles, and outline used on IHOD blog today if you would like to host one for a friend or family member!

A street photographer took this photo of my grandparents out and about in San Antonio, TX with their first born son in December 1941. They went on to have 13 children (my dad being the 10th), and were married for 74 years. They always had very little materially speaking, but their home was always full + their kitchen always open and welcome to whoever were lucky enough to sit at their table.

If you’d like to copy an old photo, you can have it printed as an engineer black and white print for a pretty great price at places like Staples, OfficeMax, or @parabopress.

I have found some of my best frames at thrift or antique stores. You can also find good sized frames at Michael’s and even Amazon (linked some in my stories). I had this special photo custom framed at Framebridge in their antique gold frame.

Photos can make the most treasured gifts. I miss my grandparents dearly, but this is a way to keep their memory alive in our home. 🤍

Our advent and Christmastime traditions 👇🏽🎄✨

Sibling gift exchange - The kids each draw a sibling name at the beginning of advent, and exchange gifts on Christmas Eve. They gift something they already own or something they make.

Decorating the tree- It’s become one of our favorite nights of the year. We make a night of it with hit cocoa, vintage records, and/or a Christmas movie.

Basket of Christmas books by the tree- we have slowly collected Christmas books over the years and we bring them out of storage for December and keep them by the tree. Always amazed by how entertained my kids are by these! (We have a list of favorites on IHOD.)

Advent readings/light candles around the advent wreath. The kids take turns doing the readings, and we sing O Come O Come Emmanuel. Takes ten minutes but reminds us each night of the hopeful waiting of advent.

Put out shoes or stockings on the eve of St. Nicholas Day (Dec 6th) - Little gold coins, oranges, and a few little surprises.

Make easy cinnamon rolls for neighbors. A simple way to serve community me friends alike.

What are some of your favorite family traditions? I love hearing from each of you in different parts of the country or across the globe! 🤍

Star Bread Recipe ✨ I share this every year because it’s one of our favorites to make and eat;) A fun one for holiday gatherings, and little ones.

Dough ingredients:
(You can use pillsbury dough sheets as a shortcut.)
* 1 cup warm milk
* 1 tablespoon instant dry yeast
* 2 tablespoons white granulated sugar
* 1 teaspoon salt
* 3 tablespoons salted butter softened
* 1 large egg
* 3 cups all-purpose flour (add more if needed until dough forms)

Other ingredients needed:
- 1 jar nutella or jam 
- About 1 stick of butter at room temp 
- Powdered sugar to sprinkle on top

INSTRUCTIONS
For dough: 
In a mixer, combine warm milk, yeast, sugar, salt, butter, and eggs. Add in flour. Use a dough hook and turn on to a low to medium speed until dough is formed. Place a lightly greased mixing bowl. Cover with a towel and let rise until double in size, about 1 hour.

 For star bread:
1.  Divide dough into 4 even pieces, and let sit for another 15 min. 
2. Roll first dough piece into a 10”-11″ circle onto parchment paper.
3. Place a bowl on top to trim edges.
4. Spread a layer of softened butter followed by a layer of Nutella leaving a little space around the edges.
5. Repeat with two more layers.
6. Lay the 4th layer of dough on top, and lay a 3”-4” circular object at the center. (I used a mug top.)
7. Use a knife or scissors to make 12 evenly cut sections of dough.
8. Take two side by side sections, and twist them away from each other two and half times.
9. Pinch the ends together well. 
10. Repeat with the remaining dough until you have a *6* point star.
11. Brush with melted butter.
12. Let the star bread sit for 30 min. 
Bake at 350° for about 20 min. or until slightly golden.
Remove from oven and sprinkle with powdered sugar. 

Best served warm with family, friends, or the neighbor who needs company this holiday season. 😉

Your annual reminder to add croissants to your grocery cart this weekend;) 🥐 I like how you can prep this the day before, refrigerate overnight, and stick it in the oven Christmas morning so you can enjoy time with your family. 

I usually get my croissants from Costco the week of Christmas, because they are large and inexpensive! They can sit out a day or a few days before you use them for this strata, so they are a little stale; it allows for a better overall (less soggy) texture.

Ingredients:
7-8 large day-old croissants
5 eggs
1 c. cream
1 c. milk
A couple dashes of salt and a pinch of pepper
1/2 tsp. garlic powder
1/4 tsp. cayenne pepper
2 tbsp. dijon mustard
1/3 c. chopped green onions
2 c. thin sliced ham, chopped into pieces (can substitute with bacon or sausage!)
1 c. shredded cheddar or gouda
1 1/2 c. shredded cheddar or gouda for topping

Instructions:
-Tear apart croissants into chunks and arrange in buttered 9×13 Pyrex dish.
-Toast in the oven for 3 min. on 400°
-In a mixing bowl, beat eggs. Mix in cream, milk, salt, pepper, garlic powder, cayenne pepper, dijon mustard, green onions, ham, and cheese.
-Pour mixture over toasted croissant pieces, and use a fork to spread out evenly.
-Sprinkle shredded gruyere, swiss, or whatever cheese you have on hand on top!
-Cover with greased foil and refrigerate for an hour (but best overnight!).
-Bake on convection setting at 350° for 45 min. You can remove foil for last ten minutes if you want it a little toasty on top!
-Serve warm with a side of fresh fruit! 
(Makes 12 servings.)

Creamy Gnocchi Recipe:
2 16 oz. packages Gnocchi
6-8 medium tomatoes chopped into quarters (I have used baby tomatoes as well.)
½ c. Heavy cream
8 oz. burratta or mozarella pearls (Burrata is harder to find, but creamier!)
Salt and pepper to taste
1 package of basil leaves

- Preheat large skillet with a few tablespoons of olive oil on medium low.
-Chop tomatoes and place in skillet to cook (lid on) until soft and saucey.
-Add salt and pepper and stir.
-Cook gnocchi according to package directions while tomatoes simmer.
-Pour in heavy cream into tomato sauce, and turn down to low.
-Drain gnocchi and add into tomato sauce, stirring to mix until covered In sauce.
-Add in burrata or mozarella and top with basil leaves (I have done spinach as well to sneak in more veggies.)
-Dish up and enjoy!

Italians-feel free to weigh in on any tomato sauce tips! 🍅
